		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>A most emphatic yes!&nbsp;&nbsp;Paladins are, without deviation, unswervingly good.  However, on the D&D scale of things, Dal would be Chaotic Good, which means he wouldn't be a Paladin...  (A better way of describing Dal would be a rogue Paladin; not officially sponsored by the Knights of Truth or Passion, but still good and still has his paladin abilities.)<br><br>However, this is beside the point.  No.  Paladins are not evil.  Under D&D rules (I believe someone's said this already, though, but it bears repeating..), a paladin that does not remain Lawful Good, or does even one act of evil (willingly or unwillingly), immediately loses his/her paladin abilities.  If the act is done willingly, it is impossible to recover them; if the act is done unwillingly or unwittingly, then the paladin can atone and get them back.<br><br>The long and the short: if you want to be evil, be a shadowknight.  Otherwise, be good.<br><br>Dalantia<br>Rogue Knight of Passion, 17th Rank<br>Fennin Ro<br>Unguilded</p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Dalantia Dragonfury<br>Crusader of the Burning Heart, 60th Protection, Third Blessing<br>Fennin Ro<br>New Dawnings<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=60479" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=60479</a></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
